																				not go up by 10% on any of the target dates?</strong> <br />
																			The investor gets the principal invested back which
																			lets say, is 20 lacs. The Rs.60,000 – one time
																			investment fee is gone and there is an interest loss
																			for 3.3 years. If we assume a conservative interest
																			of 6% p.a., the opportunity loss would&nbsp;be
																			Rs.4,24,000.
																			<p>The product offers returns
																				which&nbsp;might&nbsp;be,&nbsp;at best 3%&nbsp;above
																				the FMP returns (assuming 9% as FMP Returns) or 3%
																				to 4% above the FD returns. If the condition is not
																				met on trigger date, the returns&nbsp;would be 0%.</p> <strong>What
																				happens if Nifty goes up by more than 10%?</strong> <br />
																			Even if the Nifty gives returns of more than 10%, you
																			will not get advantage of the upside of equity and
																			will at best get the 11.82% returns. Even though it
																			is a miniscule possibility, say the bull’s prediction
																			of 25000 Sensex happens in the next 15 months, what
																			then will the cost of opportunity lost be? <br /> <br />
																			So, for an outflow of Rs.20.6 lacs, you could get
																			back anywhere between Rs. 20 lacs to Rs.29.60 lacs
																			anytime between 1.5 years to 3.3 years. <br /> <br />
																			All in all, this is a complex product which gives
																			debt+ returns (capped at 11.82% CAGR) by taking the
																			risk of equity. You run the risk of losing the
																			upfront charges of 3% and not earning any interest on
																			your investment for 40 months if Nifty doesn't
																			perform as expected. And if the Nifty performs well,
																			you risk losing a good part of possible equity
																			returns. <br /> <br /> We think, keeping it simple
																			with a fair allocation to debt and equity in
																			understandable and low cost products would benefit
																			your financial health far better than these fancy
																			confusers. <br /> <br /> - Vinita Somaiya, Sr.
